127
00:06:04,869 --> 00:06:07,955
Now, Homer,
you do have big bones.

128
00:06:08,039 --> 00:06:11,459
Marge, no one gains
30 pounds of bone.

129
00:06:11,542 --> 00:06:13,878
(breathing heavily)
I'm going on a diet.

130
00:06:13,961 --> 00:06:15,546
From this day forward,

131
00:06:15,630 --> 00:06:17,965
I pledge there will be
no pork chop too succulent,

132
00:06:18,049 --> 00:06:19,967
no doughnut too tasty,

133
00:06:20,051 --> 00:06:23,054
no pizza too laden
with delicious topping,

134
00:06:23,137 --> 00:06:25,056
to prevent me from reaching

135
00:06:25,139 --> 00:06:27,934
my scientifically determined
ideal weight.

136
00:06:28,017 --> 00:06:33,064
As God is my witness,
I'll always be hungry again!

137
00:06:33,147 --> 00:06:34,232
(stomach gurgling)

138
00:06:34,315 --> 00:06:35,691
D'oh! Shut up!

139
00:06:40,405 --> 00:06:43,699
This old attic's kind of
spooky, isn't it, boy?

140
00:06:43,783 --> 00:06:45,076
I said, isn't it, boy?

141
00:06:45,159 --> 00:06:46,077
-(switch clicks)
-Ahh!

142
00:06:46,160 --> 00:06:47,328
(stammers)

143
00:06:47,412 --> 00:06:49,455
Don't ever do
that to me again.

144
00:06:49,539 --> 00:06:51,249
-Okay.
-D'oh! Bart!

145
00:06:51,332 --> 00:06:53,292
(cries out)
Get away from that thing

146
00:06:53,376 --> 00:06:54,710
and help me find
my athletic equipment.

147
00:06:54,794 --> 00:06:56,212
-(mouse squeaks)
-Hmm.

148
00:06:56,295 --> 00:06:58,089
Hey, Homer,
I found your weights.

149
00:06:58,172 --> 00:07:00,591
Oh, the glutemus maximizer.

150
00:07:00,675 --> 00:07:02,760
Hey! Who's the mop top
with the big schnozz?

151
00:07:02,844 --> 00:07:06,389
Don't you know anything, boy?
That's Ringo Starr.

152
00:07:06,472 --> 00:07:08,516
What is this?

153
00:07:08,599 --> 00:07:11,436
Hey, your mother
must have painted this.

154
00:07:11,519 --> 00:07:13,855
I guess she thought
he was kinda cute.

155
00:07:13,938 --> 00:07:15,398
What? Hey!

156
00:07:15,481 --> 00:07:16,732
What the--

157
00:07:16,816 --> 00:07:18,234
Marge!

158
00:07:18,317 --> 00:07:19,819
No, Homer.

159
00:07:19,902 --> 00:07:21,779
Don't be jealous.
I was a schoolgirl.

160
00:07:21,863 --> 00:07:23,906
The Beatles were very popular,
and I had a crush on them.

161
00:07:23,990 --> 00:07:25,241
Likely story.

162
00:07:26,576 --> 00:07:28,744
Oh, why did I have
to start my diet

163
00:07:28,828 --> 00:07:30,329
on pork chop night?

164
00:07:30,413 --> 00:07:33,082
Now Homer,
we've got steamed vegetables

165
00:07:33,166 --> 00:07:34,959
and rice cakes for you.

166
00:07:35,042 --> 00:07:36,878
(shudders)
Well, wait a minute.

167
00:07:36,961 --> 00:07:39,547
Well, hey, I've been setting
my drinks on these things.

168
00:07:39,630 --> 00:07:41,591
Well, they're only
35 calories apiece.

169
00:07:44,469 --> 00:07:46,012
Hello? Hello?

170
00:07:46,095 --> 00:07:48,181
Hello, taste?
Where are you?

171
00:07:48,264 --> 00:07:51,017
You can put a little
something on top for flavor.

172
00:07:51,100 --> 00:07:52,518
Hey, hey,
now you're talking.

173
00:07:52,602 --> 00:07:54,562
Hey, Mom!
These paintings are good.

174
00:07:54,645 --> 00:07:57,231
While I know firsthand
how fragile young talent is,

175
00:07:57,315 --> 00:07:59,984
I'd love to hear the particulars
of how your gift was squashed.

176
00:08:00,067 --> 00:08:01,360
(groans)
Well...

177
00:08:03,488 --> 00:08:05,531
(scoffs)
No, not another portrait

178
00:08:05,615 --> 00:08:07,241
of that bongo-beating
Liverpudlian.

179
00:08:07,325 --> 00:08:08,367
But Mr. Schindler, I--

180
00:08:08,451 --> 00:08:10,786
Someone might have
used this canvas

181
00:08:10,870 --> 00:08:12,497
to create a masterpiece.

182
00:08:12,580 --> 00:08:15,166
Instead, you've
soiled it forever.

183
00:08:15,249 --> 00:08:18,419
-Now, this is art.
-Thank you, Mr. Schindler.

184
00:08:18,503 --> 00:08:21,005
LISA: <i>Oh, Mom, I can't</i>
<i>believe you gave up painting</i>

185
00:08:21,088 --> 00:08:24,175
<i>because of one</i>
<i>small-minded art teacher.</i>

186
00:08:24,258 --> 00:08:27,094
MARGE: <i>I was so upset,</i>
<i>I decided to send the portrait</i>

187
00:08:27,178 --> 00:08:29,931
<i>to the only man on Earth whose</i>
<i>opinion I could really trust.</i>

188
00:08:30,014 --> 00:08:32,225
LISA:
<i>And what was Ringo's response?</i>

189
00:08:32,308 --> 00:08:35,561
Mmm, I never got any,
and I never painted again.

190
00:08:35,645 --> 00:08:38,105
Maybe you could take a class
at Springfield Community College.

191
00:08:38,189 --> 00:08:40,691
I think it's
a very nice idea.

192
00:08:40,775 --> 00:08:42,485
-Don't you, Homer?
-Do I have to do anything?

193
00:08:42,568 --> 00:08:44,028
-No.
-Great! Fine!

194
00:08:44,111 --> 00:08:45,571
-Go nuts! Hee-hee-hee.
-(timer dings)

195
00:08:45,655 --> 00:08:49,659
-Mmm! Only 35 calories.
-(groans)

196
00:08:53,663 --> 00:08:55,164
Oh, hello, Mrs. Homer.

197
00:08:55,248 --> 00:08:57,208
Apu, what are you
doing here?

198
00:08:57,291 --> 00:08:59,252
I've just enrolled in
the screenwriting class.

199
00:08:59,335 --> 00:09:02,713
I yearn to tell the story
of an idealistic young Hindu

200
00:09:02,797 --> 00:09:06,050
pushed too far
by convenience store bandits.

201
00:09:06,133 --> 00:09:08,469
I call it
"Hands Off My Jerky, Turkey."

202
00:09:08,553 --> 00:09:10,680
-Clever title.
-Oh, thank you.

203
00:09:10,763 --> 00:09:12,306
Actually my brother
Sanjay thought of it.

204
00:09:12,390 --> 00:09:14,267
-Next up.
-My mother would like to enroll

205
00:09:14,350 --> 00:09:16,310
in "Painting From Life" 2-B,
please.

206
00:09:16,394 --> 00:09:18,854
Whoa, whoa, whoa.
Not so fast there, pint-size.

207
00:09:18,938 --> 00:09:21,482
I'm afraid no one can enroll
until Professor Lombardo

208
00:09:21,566 --> 00:09:23,985
personally inspects and
approves their portfolio.

209
00:09:24,068 --> 00:09:27,238
-Lisa, this was a bad idea.
-Mom!

210
00:09:27,321 --> 00:09:31,284
Ah, very good.
Fabulous!

211
00:09:31,367 --> 00:09:33,327
Ah, even better.

212
00:09:33,411 --> 00:09:34,954
You have real talent.

213
00:09:35,037 --> 00:09:36,664
Hmm. Do you
really think so?

214
00:09:36,747 --> 00:09:38,583
My high school
art teacher hated them.

215
00:09:38,666 --> 00:09:40,626
What? The man was a fool.

216
00:09:40,710 --> 00:09:43,629
But still, one must admire
the force of his conviction.

217
00:09:43,713 --> 00:09:45,673
-Then I'm in the class?
-Oh, my dear,

218
00:09:45,756 --> 00:09:47,550
there couldn't be a class
without you.

219
00:09:47,633 --> 00:09:51,053
Now, if you'll excuse me,
nature calls.

220
00:09:51,137 --> 00:09:53,139
Marvelous!

221
00:09:53,222 --> 00:09:57,226
(straining)
Stupid weights.

222
00:09:57,310 --> 00:10:00,187
The heavy hands don't work
unless you move, Homer.

223
00:10:00,271 --> 00:10:01,897
I can't move, boy.

224
00:10:01,981 --> 00:10:03,190
Oh, really?

225
00:10:03,274 --> 00:10:06,360
(grunting)
Oh!

226
00:10:06,444 --> 00:10:09,113
Now, using the Lombardo method,

227
00:10:09,196 --> 00:10:11,907
you learn to see
everyday objects

228
00:10:11,991 --> 00:10:14,577
as a simple grouping
of geometrical shapes.

229
00:10:14,660 --> 00:10:18,080
Here, we see how
two concentric circles

230
00:10:18,164 --> 00:10:19,540
various trapezoids, ellipsis--

231
00:10:19,624 --> 00:10:21,751
and yes, even a rhombus--

232
00:10:21,834 --> 00:10:25,421
can create an adorable
little bunny rabbit.

233
00:10:25,504 --> 00:10:27,256
It's just that easy!

234
00:10:27,340 --> 00:10:28,716
(groaning)

235
00:10:28,799 --> 00:10:32,428
(straining)

236
00:10:32,511 --> 00:10:34,430
<i>♪ Lincoln, Lincoln,</i>
<i>I've been thinkin' ♪</i>

237
00:10:34,513 --> 00:10:36,432
<i>♪ What the hell</i>
<i>have you been drinkin'? ♪</i>

238
00:10:36,515 --> 00:10:38,434
<i>♪ Is it water, is it wine? ♪</i>

239
00:10:38,517 --> 00:10:40,645
<i>♪ Oh, my gosh,</i>
<i>it's turpentine ♪</i>

240
00:10:40,728 --> 00:10:43,397
-(both cheering)
-Go! Go! Go!

241
00:10:43,481 --> 00:10:45,566
♪♪

242
00:10:45,650 --> 00:10:46,984
(cat screeching)

243
00:10:52,406 --> 00:10:53,949
Bravo!

244
00:10:54,033 --> 00:10:56,327
Walk away from it.
Now it belongs to the ages.

245
00:10:56,410 --> 00:10:57,703
You. Not another stroke.

246
00:10:57,787 --> 00:11:01,040
Oh, well, maybe one more.
That's it! Perfect!

247
00:11:01,123 --> 00:11:03,250
Mmm... indeed.

248
00:11:03,334 --> 00:11:05,461
Marge, you find
the inner beauty

249
00:11:05,544 --> 00:11:07,338
of your subject
and bring it out for all to see.

250
00:11:07,421 --> 00:11:08,881
Well, thank you,
Professor Lombardo.

251
00:11:08,964 --> 00:11:10,966
Well, you're welcome,
my dear.

252
00:11:11,050 --> 00:11:13,636
-(quietly) Marge, walk with me.
-(Marge groans)

253
00:11:13,719 --> 00:11:16,097
Marge, they've asked <i>me</i>

254
00:11:16,180 --> 00:11:18,015
to submit the best painting
from my class

255
00:11:18,099 --> 00:11:20,726
to the Springfield
Art Exhibition next week.

256
00:11:20,810 --> 00:11:24,814
I've decided to choose
your <i>Bald Adonis.</i>

257
00:11:24,897 --> 00:11:26,774
Really?
You're so supportive.

258
00:11:26,857 --> 00:11:28,693
I wish every teacher
was like you.

259
00:11:28,776 --> 00:11:31,529
Marge, please, I don't take
praise very well!

260
00:11:32,780 --> 00:11:35,324
Oh! Another triumph!

261
00:11:38,828 --> 00:11:40,454
Hmm.

262
00:11:41,664 --> 00:11:42,623
Hmm.

263
00:11:42,707 --> 00:11:44,250
Hmm.

264
00:11:46,419 --> 00:11:47,420
Hmm.

265
00:11:47,503 --> 00:11:48,796
Yeah.

266
00:11:48,879 --> 00:11:50,840
-I can't believe it!
-(applause)

267
00:11:50,923 --> 00:11:52,091
-Yeah!
-Go Mom!

268
00:11:52,174 --> 00:11:53,300
-All right!
-Whoo-hoo!

269
00:11:53,384 --> 00:11:54,927
I'm a work of art!

270
00:11:55,010 --> 00:11:57,054
"Last Supper,"
eat your heart out.

271
00:11:57,138 --> 00:11:59,056
-(kissing)
-(camera shutters clicking)

272
00:12:00,141 --> 00:12:01,475
Garbage!

273
00:12:01,559 --> 00:12:04,103
What matchbook art school
did you flunk out of?

274
00:12:04,186 --> 00:12:06,313
You ham-fisted
nearsighted house painter!

275
00:12:06,397 --> 00:12:08,023
Smithers,
throw this on the dung heap.

276
00:12:08,107 --> 00:12:09,775
I'm sorry.
This isn't working out. I quit.

277
00:12:09,859 --> 00:12:11,652
-Well, Smithers,
-(door slams)

278
00:12:11,736 --> 00:12:13,028
I guess that's what you call
your artistic temperament.

279
00:12:13,112 --> 00:12:16,365
Sir, I must remind you
that the dedication

280
00:12:16,449 --> 00:12:18,617
of the Burns Wing of the museum
is only six days away.

281
00:12:18,701 --> 00:12:21,662
Damnation, Smithers.
This idea of yours to immortalize me

282
00:12:21,746 --> 00:12:23,372
in a portrait
was as half-baked

283
00:12:23,456 --> 00:12:25,374
as your idea about
me having children.

284
00:12:25,458 --> 00:12:27,042
Smithers, find me an artist.

285
00:12:27,126 --> 00:12:30,129
Sir, I'm afraid you've
systematically alienated

286
00:12:30,212 --> 00:12:31,964
Springfield's entire
art community.

287
00:12:32,047 --> 00:12:34,508
The only one left is
this Mrs. Homer Simpson.

288
00:12:34,592 --> 00:12:36,635
-Who?
-Well, she won first prize

289
00:12:36,719 --> 00:12:38,804
in the Springfield Art Fair,
and is the wife of an employee.

290
00:12:38,888 --> 00:12:40,556
-She'll be easily intimidated.
-Excellent.

291
00:12:40,639 --> 00:12:43,142
Once again,
the wheel has turned,

292
00:12:43,225 --> 00:12:46,562
and dame fortune
has hugged Montgomery Burns

293
00:12:46,645 --> 00:12:48,981
to her sweet,
perfumed bosom.

294
00:12:49,064 --> 00:12:50,983
Somebody up there
likes me, Smithers.

295
00:12:51,066 --> 00:12:52,359
SMITHERS: Somebody down here
likes you too, sir.

296
00:12:52,443 --> 00:12:53,778
BURNS: Shut up!

297
00:12:56,322 --> 00:12:58,574
♪♪ (Western showdown music)

298
00:13:01,577 --> 00:13:03,913
D'oh! Whoo!

299
00:13:03,996 --> 00:13:05,706
D'oh! Whoo!

300
00:13:05,790 --> 00:13:07,082
D'oh! Whoo!
D'oh! Whoo!

301
00:13:07,166 --> 00:13:09,126
D'oh! Whoo-hoo!
D'oh! Whoo-hoo!

302
00:13:09,210 --> 00:13:10,628
D'oh! Whoo-hoo!
Whoo-hoo!

303
00:13:10,711 --> 00:13:13,881
249! Yeah! Wa! Wa! Wa!

304
00:13:13,964 --> 00:13:16,717
Marge! Marge!
Look at me.

305
00:13:16,801 --> 00:13:18,677
My clothes are just
hanging off me.

306
00:13:18,761 --> 00:13:20,513
That's wonderful,
isn't it, kids?

307
00:13:20,596 --> 00:13:22,264
Pass the moo juice.

308
00:13:22,348 --> 00:13:23,849
Kids, remember what I told you
about showing a little support?

309
00:13:23,933 --> 00:13:26,769
-Way to go, Dad!
-You look <i>mah-velous.</i>

310
00:13:26,852 --> 00:13:28,437
Oh, what a family.

311
00:13:28,521 --> 00:13:30,022
Hey, what gives?

312
00:13:30,105 --> 00:13:31,816
These doughnuts are piling up.

313
00:13:31,899 --> 00:13:34,276
Huh. Yeah, Homer Simpson
went on a diet.

314
00:13:34,360 --> 00:13:37,696
Oh, my God,
and I just bought a boat.

315
00:13:42,326 --> 00:13:43,911
(straining)

316
00:13:43,994 --> 00:13:45,329
(tap)

317
00:13:45,412 --> 00:13:48,499
Well, don't people answer
the door these days?

318
00:13:48,582 --> 00:13:49,542
Allow me, sir.

319
00:13:49,625 --> 00:13:52,670
Open up! Open up!

320
00:13:52,753 --> 00:13:56,590
Mr. Burns. Oh, would
you like to come in?

321
00:13:56,674 --> 00:13:59,343
Mr. Burns would like to commission you
to do a portrait of him.

322
00:13:59,426 --> 00:14:01,262
Have you ever painted
the rich and powerful?

323
00:14:01,345 --> 00:14:03,472
Well, no. Just Ringo Starr.

324
00:14:03,556 --> 00:14:04,932
Ring-go?

325
00:14:05,015 --> 00:14:06,642
He was the drummer
for a rock and roll combo

326
00:14:06,725 --> 00:14:07,893
called The Beatles, sir.

327
00:14:07,977 --> 00:14:11,021
Beatles, eh? Oh, yes.
I seem to remember

328
00:14:11,105 --> 00:14:14,066
their off-key caterwauling
on the old Sullivan show.

329
00:14:14,149 --> 00:14:15,276
What was Ed thinking?

330
00:14:15,359 --> 00:14:17,194
Mrs. Simpson,
this commission

331
00:14:17,278 --> 00:14:20,030
and all of its glory
can be yours

332
00:14:20,114 --> 00:14:21,949
but first you must look me
straight in the eye

333
00:14:22,032 --> 00:14:23,617
and answer one
simple question.

334
00:14:23,701 --> 00:14:26,287
-Okay, shoot.
-Can you make me beautiful?

335
00:14:26,370 --> 00:14:28,539
Hmm. Well, I don't think
that will be a problem.

336
00:14:28,622 --> 00:14:30,583
I'm no matinee idol,
you know.

337
00:14:30,666 --> 00:14:32,751
Well, maybe not,
but I have the gift

338
00:14:32,835 --> 00:14:34,837
of being able
to see inner beauty.

339
00:14:34,920 --> 00:14:38,424
Hmm. Mrs. Simpson,
you may immortalize me.

340
00:14:38,507 --> 00:14:40,593
Ah, sir,

341
00:14:40,676 --> 00:14:43,345
at last the world will
see you as I always have.

342
00:14:43,429 --> 00:14:45,973
Yes, yes, yes. Now, don't be stingy
with the blush, Smithers.

343
00:14:46,056 --> 00:14:47,016
There. There.

344
00:14:50,019 --> 00:14:51,478
Now, you-- paint!

345
00:14:51,562 --> 00:14:52,605
(groaning)

346
00:14:54,398 --> 00:14:55,441
Honey, I'm home.

347
00:14:55,524 --> 00:14:56,859
Oh, there's an
original sentiment.

348
00:14:56,942 --> 00:14:57,902
(screams)

349
00:14:57,985 --> 00:14:59,445
Take it outside, Simpson.

350
00:14:59,528 --> 00:15:00,821
I'm male modeling.

351
00:15:00,905 --> 00:15:02,448
I'm painting
his portrait, Homer.

352
00:15:02,531 --> 00:15:05,117
(laughing)
Isn't that wonderful?

353
00:15:05,200 --> 00:15:07,828
My work and my home life
come together

354
00:15:07,912 --> 00:15:09,872
in such a nice way.

355
00:15:09,955 --> 00:15:11,624
Marge, may I see you
in the other room?

356
00:15:11,707 --> 00:15:13,375
Honey, he's nuts.
He thinks he's handsome.

357
00:15:13,459 --> 00:15:14,835
Please, you've got
to make him look handsome.

358
00:15:14,919 --> 00:15:16,503
Please, please, please,
please, please, please, please.

359
00:15:16,587 --> 00:15:18,047
Now, Homer, don't worry.

360
00:15:18,130 --> 00:15:21,008
All I need to do is find
Mr. Burns' inner beauty.

361
00:15:21,091 --> 00:15:23,552
Ohh! Okay.

362
00:15:23,636 --> 00:15:28,098
Hmm. What were you like
as a boy, Mr. Burns?

363
00:15:28,182 --> 00:15:29,683
Did you have a dog
that you loved?

364
00:15:29,767 --> 00:15:31,393
Well...
(cries out)

365
00:15:31,477 --> 00:15:33,938
There's something on my leg!
Get it off! Get it off!

366
00:15:34,021 --> 00:15:36,732
-Mr. Burns, she's just a baby.
-BURNS: Ugh!

367
00:15:39,151 --> 00:15:40,402
All right, all right.

368
00:15:40,486 --> 00:15:42,696
Who took the funny pages?

369
00:15:42,780 --> 00:15:44,865
So Ziggy goes
to the repair shop,

370
00:15:44,949 --> 00:15:46,909
and there's a sign
on the doorbell reading

371
00:15:46,992 --> 00:15:48,869
-"Out of order."
-(chuckles)

372
00:15:48,953 --> 00:15:52,206
Ah, Ziggy, will you ever win?

373
00:15:54,041 --> 00:15:55,376
(humming tune)

374
00:15:55,459 --> 00:15:57,878
-Oh, my!
-If you'll excuse me,

375
00:15:57,962 --> 00:15:59,964
I'm changing
for a board meeting.

376
00:16:00,047 --> 00:16:02,424
I'm so sorry, Mr. Burns.

377
00:16:02,508 --> 00:16:05,010
Hey, Mom, did he have
those spots all over his body?

378
00:16:05,094 --> 00:16:06,595
-I heard that.
-Oops.

379
00:16:06,679 --> 00:16:08,973
Would you feel more comfortable
if I left, too, sir?

380
00:16:09,056 --> 00:16:12,393
Of course not, Smithers.
You're... you're like a doctor.

381
00:16:12,476 --> 00:16:14,144
(kettle whistling)

382
00:16:14,228 --> 00:16:16,480
BURNS: Smithers,
I want my tea!

383
00:16:16,563 --> 00:16:18,732
Doesn't it bother you that
he orders you around like that?

384
00:16:18,816 --> 00:16:22,152
(chuckles) Actually, I value
every second we're together

385
00:16:22,236 --> 00:16:24,738
from the moment I squeeze
his orange juice in the morning

386
00:16:24,822 --> 00:16:26,532
till I tuck him in at night.

387
00:16:26,615 --> 00:16:29,034
He's not just my boss.
He's my best friend, too.

388
00:16:29,118 --> 00:16:30,703
Bah! Too hot!

389
00:16:30,786 --> 00:16:31,954
You're right, sir.

390
00:16:32,037 --> 00:16:33,414
It's scalding me
as we speak.

391
00:16:33,497 --> 00:16:34,873
(gasps, grumbles)

392
00:16:37,918 --> 00:16:39,461
Dear Sally.

393
00:16:39,545 --> 00:16:42,798
In response to your letter
of December 12, 1966,

394
00:16:42,881 --> 00:16:44,800
me favorite color is blue,

395
00:16:44,883 --> 00:16:46,427
and me real first name
is Richard.

396
00:16:46,510 --> 00:16:48,595
-(bell dings)
-Thanks for the snapshot.

397
00:16:48,679 --> 00:16:51,557
-You're a real cute bird. Love, Ringo.
-(bell dinging)

398
00:16:51,640 --> 00:16:53,892
P.S. Forgive the lateness
of my reply.

399
00:16:53,976 --> 00:16:56,729
-Mr. Starr, tea and crumpets.
-Just set it over there.

400
00:16:56,812 --> 00:16:59,481
Sir, if you'll forgive an old
Brit his impertinence,

401
00:16:59,565 --> 00:17:01,734
your devotion to your fans
is nothing short of remarkable.

402
00:17:01,817 --> 00:17:04,445
Well, Weatherby, they took
the time to write me,

403
00:17:04,528 --> 00:17:07,740
and I don't care
if it takes me another 20 years.

404
00:17:07,823 --> 00:17:10,409
I'm going to answer
every one of them.

405
00:17:10,492 --> 00:17:12,995
Hello. What's this?

406
00:17:13,078 --> 00:17:16,415
From Springfield, U.S.A.

407
00:17:16,498 --> 00:17:17,624
Gear.

408
00:17:20,502 --> 00:17:22,546
♪♪

409
00:17:22,629 --> 00:17:25,340
Will you cease
that infernal tootling?

410
00:17:25,424 --> 00:17:27,301
-I was just practicing.
-(groans)

411
00:17:27,384 --> 00:17:30,054
Mr. Burns, it's hard to
discover your inner beauty

412
00:17:30,137 --> 00:17:32,139
while you're shouting
at an eight-year-old girl.

413
00:17:32,222 --> 00:17:35,017
We've only got two days left,
so I'd advise you to shut up and paint!

414
00:17:35,100 --> 00:17:36,060
(groans)

415
00:17:36,143 --> 00:17:37,478
All right scale,

416
00:17:37,561 --> 00:17:39,271
you don't like me
and I don't like you,

417
00:17:39,354 --> 00:17:41,982
but I've been very good,
so you'd better treat me right.

418
00:17:42,066 --> 00:17:44,568
All right! Whoa-ho-ho!

419
00:17:44,651 --> 00:17:46,403
Whoo! Whoo!

420
00:17:46,487 --> 00:17:50,491
Marge, I'm 239
and I'm feeling fine.

421
00:17:50,574 --> 00:17:53,368
Look, I'm using the original
notches that came with my belt.

422
00:17:53,452 --> 00:17:56,038
That's wonderful, Homer.
I'm so proud of--

423
00:17:56,121 --> 00:17:57,664
Let me get this straight.

424
00:17:57,748 --> 00:18:01,168
You're pleased
with your current appearance?

425
00:18:01,251 --> 00:18:03,670
(laughs)
Why, my good man,

426
00:18:03,754 --> 00:18:05,589
you're the fattest thing
I've ever seen

427
00:18:05,672 --> 00:18:07,508
-and I've been on safari.
-(chuckling)

428
00:18:07,591 --> 00:18:10,427
(crying) If you need me,
I'll be in the refrigerator.

429
00:18:10,511 --> 00:18:13,138
-(sobbing)
-(groaning)

430
00:18:13,222 --> 00:18:16,642
Mr. Burns, I've had enough
of your posing.

431
00:18:16,725 --> 00:18:18,685
I can finish
the portrait myself.

432
00:18:18,769 --> 00:18:21,480
Thank goodness. Another day
in this suburban nightmare,

433
00:18:21,563 --> 00:18:22,981
and I would have needed
half a white Valium.

434
00:18:23,065 --> 00:18:25,067
Thank you for your
gracious hospitality.

435
00:18:25,150 --> 00:18:26,652
See you at the unveiling.

436
00:18:26,735 --> 00:18:28,112
(whistling)

437
00:18:29,863 --> 00:18:32,825
(gasps) Homer, what are you doing?
Give me that!

438
00:18:32,908 --> 00:18:35,661
No, Burns is right.
What's the use?

439
00:18:35,744 --> 00:18:38,539
Don't you listen to him.
He's just a mean, little S.O.B.

440
00:18:38,622 --> 00:18:40,457
Oh, Marge.

441
00:18:40,541 --> 00:18:42,334
I thought there was
some good in everybody

442
00:18:42,417 --> 00:18:44,586
-until I met him.
-Yeah, well,

443
00:18:44,670 --> 00:18:46,463
just as long as you paint
a nice picture of him by noon tomorrow.

444
00:18:46,547 --> 00:18:47,965
-I don't think I can.
-What?

445
00:18:48,048 --> 00:18:49,091
Marge, you have to!

446
00:18:49,174 --> 00:18:50,676
I can't make that man
beautiful!

447
00:18:50,759 --> 00:18:52,886
I'm just not good enough.

448
00:18:52,970 --> 00:18:54,513
I guess I'm no artist.

449
00:18:54,596 --> 00:18:57,141
Hmm. Hello. What's this?

450
00:18:57,224 --> 00:19:00,352
It's for you, Marge,
from merry old England.

451
00:19:00,435 --> 00:19:02,104
"From the desk
of Ringo Starr."

452
00:19:02,187 --> 00:19:03,814
RINGO:
<i>"Dear Marge.</i>

453
00:19:03,897 --> 00:19:06,483
<i>"Thanks for the fab painting</i>
<i>of yours truly.</i>

454
00:19:06,567 --> 00:19:08,277
<i>"I hung it on me wall.</i>

455
00:19:08,360 --> 00:19:09,653
<i>"You're quite an artist.</i>

456
00:19:09,736 --> 00:19:11,446
<i>"In answer to your question--</i>

457
00:19:11,530 --> 00:19:13,907
<i>"Yes, we do have hamburgers</i>
<i>and fries in England,</i>

458
00:19:13,991 --> 00:19:16,618
<i>"but we call french fries</i>
<i>'chips.'</i>

459
00:19:16,702 --> 00:19:18,453
<i>"Love, Ringo.</i>

460
00:19:18,537 --> 00:19:20,914
<i>P.S. Forgive the lateness</i>
<i>of my reply."</i>

461
00:19:20,998 --> 00:19:24,209
-Ooh!
-Come on, Marge, paint.

462
00:19:24,293 --> 00:19:26,295
I think you can do it.

463
00:19:26,378 --> 00:19:29,590
Okay, Homer,
if you think I can.

464
00:19:29,673 --> 00:19:33,135
RINGO: <i>♪ Got to pay your dues if</i>
<i>you want to sing the blues ♪</i>

465
00:19:33,218 --> 00:19:35,971
<i>♪ And you know</i>
<i>it don't come easy ♪</i>

466
00:19:38,015 --> 00:19:40,976
<i>♪ You don't have to shout</i>
<i>or leap about ♪</i>

467
00:19:41,059 --> 00:19:44,605
<i>♪ You can even play</i>
<i>them easy ♪</i>

468
00:19:49,651 --> 00:19:52,321
(chamber music playing)

469
00:19:53,864 --> 00:19:56,533
(playing "For He's
a Jolly Good Fellow")

470
00:19:56,617 --> 00:19:59,995
Friends, art lovers,
security personnel,

471
00:20:00,078 --> 00:20:01,580
today is a red letter day

472
00:20:01,663 --> 00:20:03,498
for the Springfield Palace
of Fine Arts.

473
00:20:03,582 --> 00:20:07,002
A new wing for our museum,
ooh, and a portrait

474
00:20:07,085 --> 00:20:09,421
commemorating the man
who ponied up the dough.

475
00:20:10,756 --> 00:20:13,133
Ladies and gentlemen,
may I invite you

476
00:20:13,217 --> 00:20:17,179
to behold Montgomery Burns.

477
00:20:17,262 --> 00:20:19,890
(straining)

478
00:20:19,973 --> 00:20:21,350
Smithers.

479
00:20:24,102 --> 00:20:25,771
-(crowd gasps)
-(glass shatters)

480
00:20:25,854 --> 00:20:27,898
-Oh.
-D'oh!

481
00:20:27,981 --> 00:20:29,524
I don't care for this at all.

482
00:20:33,403 --> 00:20:36,240
Um... hello.

483
00:20:36,323 --> 00:20:40,702
My name is Marge Simpson,
and I painted this.

484
00:20:40,786 --> 00:20:43,455
Maybe you'd like to know
what possessed me to do it.

485
00:20:43,538 --> 00:20:47,125
Well, I guess I wanted to show

486
00:20:47,209 --> 00:20:50,170
that beneath Mr. Burns'
fearsome head

487
00:20:50,254 --> 00:20:52,756
with its cruel lips,
spiteful tongue

488
00:20:52,839 --> 00:20:54,549
and evil brain,

489
00:20:54,633 --> 00:20:57,261
there was a frail,
withered body,

490
00:20:57,344 --> 00:20:59,805
perhaps not long
for this world,

491
00:20:59,888 --> 00:21:04,935
as vulnerable and beautiful
as any of God's creatures.

492
00:21:05,018 --> 00:21:06,687
-(applause)
-Hmm?

493
00:21:06,770 --> 00:21:09,439
-MAN: Yes! Oh!
-(whistling)

494
00:21:09,523 --> 00:21:11,858
Provocative but, uh, powerful.

495
00:21:11,942 --> 00:21:13,944
He's bad, but he'll die.

496
00:21:14,027 --> 00:21:15,195
So I like it.

497
00:21:15,279 --> 00:21:16,571
Hmm...

498
00:21:16,655 --> 00:21:18,865
Marge, a word, please.

499
00:21:18,949 --> 00:21:21,743
You know, I'm no art critic

500
00:21:21,827 --> 00:21:26,248
but I know what I hate,
and I don't hate this.

501
00:21:26,331 --> 00:21:29,710
Your painting is bold
but beautiful

502
00:21:29,793 --> 00:21:31,336
and, incidentally,

503
00:21:31,420 --> 00:21:35,215
thanks for not making fun
of my genitalia.

504
00:21:35,299 --> 00:21:36,883
I thought I did.

505
00:21:39,970 --> 00:21:43,390
♪♪

506
